So basically I would partially agree with that twitter thread on whether we have succeeded "yet" but I dont agree where blame has been put into. I feel that is a very hollow and narrow view to blame intl organizations.END (hopefully)

If you had read all these above, what you would realize is that there are so many steps from creating insights to converting them to solutions to have governance and finance mechanisms to sustain them. Expecting successes with step one would be incorrect.

2. I think I have influenced 100s if not thousands with my insights that I post here & elsewhere. These help in building consensus w.r.t issues & future meetings would be easy for me. I am not creating solutions in twitter. Instead, I am creating the platform to propel solutions

1. I believe that I have created a benchmark on how to do analysis for decision making works that many GIS analysts, planners have been asked to recreate my works (I get notified quite often). It would help creating better insights before working on solutions

So at this point you might be thinking: "Hey Raj, what have you accomplished?"I dont believe in overnight success and that we can be prepared for any type of disaster by next year. I believe in a long process.For now I have been successful in two aspects

I mean how many of you would like to donate to an organization that would focus on influencing a master plan that would help drainage patterns rather than an organization that shows visually pleasing "lake rejuvenation" type of project which wont stand for long?

Donors love to work either on the first step of climate plans, vulnerability assessments and also on the final steps on ground implementation of something but rarely on the steps in between them. Many of the  changes w.r.t policies,masterplans, laws dont have a good audience

Another problem is that organizations (intl or local) dont tend to work on governance & finance related structural changes. Any change to current power structure would not be very welcome &organizations tend to work with existing structures so that they are not antagonized

It is necessary that solutions should be built with consensus (atleast a majority) & it is critical that the solutions are co-developed between experts, govt, & public representatives so that there is a sense of ownership. Without it, guidance reports would disappear over time

Even if reports are well prepared, it takes a lot of time to build consensus on these among public &  govts. Everyone incl me or you would come with a baggage which contains a lot of pre-conceived notions, thoughts, judgments. We can not bulldoze people with opinions & solutions

Sci-Tech experts are not passionate enough and I have noticed that many dont want to do hard work with intricate understanding of the ground situations. Activists dont have the means. With reports getting diluted, it is typically difficult for policy makers to take decisions

The analyses we do are too generic prepared from the sky & are not context specific. I love to see detailed work & I usually get criticized for the same. But my stand is that if it is not detailed enough, then we would never gain insights to convert them into meaningful solutions

To succeed, it is the locals who should work. That is where I see failure. There is no buy-in of core concepts with the local public, govt, and public representatives and that is where the failure is. There are many reasons why these fail

International organizations can NOT work on the later steps. They can provide reports and guidances alone. Their work would hence be selling the core concepts through seminars, workshops etc alone. One needs to understand their limitations

We cant acheive success from step one alone where we create reports and expect everyone to read them immediately, change their world view overnight, and get on ground and do something about it. The later steps have to be built too.

To succeed in this regard, it is necessary that we have to do these1. Detailed reports & guidances2. Conversion of insights & guidances from above into actionable items3. Changes in laws, master plans, & other operational documents4. Changes in governance & finance mechanisms
